{{for|the race horse|Birdstone}} [[File:Native American bird-shaped fetish stone, Honolulu Museum of Art 2014-3-09.JPG|alt=Flaked, banded light brown stone, shaped like a displayed bird.|thumb|Native American bird-shaped, flaked, banded, light brown stone in the [[Honolulu Museum of Art]]]] '''Bird stones''' are [[prehistoric]], [[abstract art|abstract]] stone carvings made by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]]. The artifacts were a common inclusion in graves and thought to have ceremonial importance. They are noted for their distinctive simplicity and beauty. They first appeared in the middle [[Archaic period (North America)|Archaic period]] around 5,000 years ago and continued into the early [[Woodland period]] to about 2,500 years before present.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rslive.bslcore.com/article.php?aid=3906&cid=3|title=The Enigmatic Birdstone|website=www.rslive.bslcore.com|language=en|access-date=2018-07-02}}</ref>
The exact purpose of these artifacts is not known, but most have a small hole drilled at the base of the neck and another at the aft end, presumably for mounting. Some theories suggest they were part of an [[atlatl]] (a short rod to hurl spears), in addition to their ceremonial uses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.museum.state.il.us/muslink/nat_amer/pre/htmls/a_weapons.html|title=Native Americans:Prehistoric:Archaic:Technology:Weapons|website=www.museum.state.il.us|access-date=2017-03-02}}</ref> It has also been suggested that these artifacts were worn as decorative items denoting marriage status or pregnancy,<ref name="Hodge">{{cite book|last1=Hodge|first1=Frederick Webb|title=Handbook of American Indians North of Mexico, Part 1|date=1907|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|location=Washington, DC|pages=148–149|url=https://archive.org/stream/americanindians00hodggoog#page/n2/mode/2up|ref=Hodge}}</ref> and as [[totem]]s representing tribes.<ref name="Allen">{{cite journal|last1=Allen|first1=George X.|title=The Significance of the So-Called Bird-Stone|journal=American Antiquity|date=January 1936|volume=1|issue=3|page=225|doi=10.2307/275148|jstor=275148|ref=Allen}}</ref>
Bird stones were mostly made east of the [[Mississippi]], and the thousands in existence have been found primarily in New York, Ohio, Michigan and Wisconsin.<ref>''Encyclopædia Britannica'', Micropædia, Vol II at p36</ref> The stones range in length from 3 to 6&nbsp;inches, and have unique variations in style. Most are ground from grayish green, banded [[slate]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ohioarch.org/PastArticles4.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2005-07-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050425035115/http://www.ohioarch.org/PastArticles4.htm |archivedate=2005-04-25 |df= }}</ref> and occasionally [[Porphyry (geology)|porphyry]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Bird Stones|url=http://www.britannica.com/art/bird-stone|website=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=11 February 2016|ref=Britannica}}</ref>
